    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="1412"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1412">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">823.248/354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Chief, Division of West Coast
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lyon</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">to the Director, Office of American Republic
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Duggan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-25">February 25,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Duggan</hi>: Colonel Revoredo<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d1412fn3">Col. Armando Revoredo, Peruvian Air Attaché in
                        Washington.</note> is probably coming to complain to you about the action of
                    the Munitions Assignment Committee “Air” in turning down an application by Peru
                    on February 2 for twelve dive bombers. The refusal to allow Peru to receive
                    these planes is in keeping with our policy which is not to supply combat <pb
                        facs="1519" n="1505" xml:id="pg_1505"/> planes to the other Americas which
                    are not actually engaged in the war. I believe the only exceptions are Mexico
                    and Brazil.<note n="4" xml:id="d1412fn4">For correspondence on the development
                        of a revised policy on sending weapons to the American Republics, see <ref
                            target="#pg_87">pp. 87</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>What I had in mind when I spoke to you was the attached letter from Mr.
                        Bonsal<note n="5" xml:id="d1412fn5">Philip W. Bonsal, Deputy Director,
                        Office of American Republic Affairs; letter not printed.</note> to Jeff
                        Patterson<note n="6" xml:id="d1412fn6">Jefferson Patterson, Counselor of
                        Embassy in Peru.</note> concerning a military mission for Peru, which
                    Patterson discussed when he was up here last week. I now think it unlikely,
                    however, that Revoredo would be discussing this as it seems to be a matter
                    originating with Colonel Johnson.<note n="7" xml:id="d1412fn7">Presumably Col.
                        Bayard A. C. Johnson.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
